# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-application-firewall
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] An **application firewall** is a form of firewall that controls input/output or system calls of an application or service.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] It operates by monitoring and blocking communications based on a configured policy, generally with predefined rule sets to choose from.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] The two primary categories of application firewalls are *network-based* and *host-based*.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Gene Spafford of Purdue University, Bill Cheswick at AT&T Laboratories, and Marcus Ranum described a third-generation firewall known as an application layer firewall.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Marcus Ranum's work, based on the firewall created by Paul Vixie, Brian Reid, and Jeff Mogul, spearheaded the creation of the first commercial product.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] The product was released by DEC, named the DEC SEAL by Geoff Mulligan - Secure External Access Link.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] DEC's first major sale was on June 13, 1991, to Dupont.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Under a broader DARPA contract at TIS, Marcus Ranum, Wei Xu, and Peter Churchyard developed the Firewall Toolkit (FWTK) and made it freely available under license in October 1993.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] However, FWTK was a basic application proxy requiring the user interactions.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] In 1994, Wei Xu extended the FWTK with the Kernel enhancement of IP stateful filter and socket transparent.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] This was the first transparent firewall, known as the inception of the third generation firewall, beyond a traditional application proxy (the second generation firewall), released as the commercial product known as Gauntlet firewall.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Gauntlet firewall was rated one of the top application firewalls from 1995 until 1998, the year it was acquired by Network Associates Inc, (NAI).
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Network Associates continued to claim that Gauntlet was the "worlds most secure firewall" but in May 2000, security researcher Jim Stickley discovered a large vulnerability in the firewall, allowing remote access to the operating system and bypassing the security controls.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Stickley discovered a second vulnerability a year later, effectively ending Gauntlet firewalls' security dominance.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Application layer filtering operates at a higher level than traditional security appliances.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] This allows packet decisions to be made based on more than just source/destination IP Address or ports and can also use information spanning across multiple connections for any given host.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Network-based application firewalls operate at the application layer of a TCP/IP stack and can understand certain applications and protocols such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP), Domain Name System (DNS), or Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] This allows it to identify unwanted applications or services using a non standard port or detect if an allowed protocol is being abused.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Web application firewalls (WAF) are a specialized version of a network-based appliance that acts as a reverse proxy, inspecting traffic before being forwarded to an associated server.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] A host-based application firewall monitors application system calls or other general system communication.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] This gives more granularity and control, but is limited to only protecting the host it is running on.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Control is applied by filtering on a per process basis.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Generally, prompts are used to define rules for processes that have not yet received a connection.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Further filtering can be done by examining the process ID of the owner of the data packets.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Many host-based application firewalls are combined or used in conjunction with a packet filter.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Due to technological limitations, modern solutions such as sandboxing are being used as a replacement of host-based application firewalls to protect system processes.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Application firewalls are available in various forms, including free and open-source software as well as commercial products.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Starting with Mac OS X Leopard, an implementation of the TrustedBSD MAC framework (taken from FreeBSD), was included.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] The TrustedBSD MAC framework is used to sandbox services and provides a firewall layer, given the configuration of the sharing services in Mac OS X Leopard and Snow Leopard.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] Third-party applications can provide extended functionality, including filtering out outgoing connections by app.
[src:web-application-firewall/application-firewall] These devices may be sold as hardware, software, or virtualized network appliances.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] The Transfer-Encoding header works by defining a directive on how to interpret the body of the HTTP request, with the common and necessary directive for this attack being the chunked transfer encoding.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] When the Transfer-Encoding header is present, the Content-Length header is supposed to be omitted.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] Working similarly but with a different syntax, the Content-Length header works by specifying the size in bytes of the body as a value in the header itself.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] Vulnerabilities arise when both of these headers are included in a malicious HTTP request, bypassing security functions meant to prevent malicious HTTP queries to the server by causing either the front-end or back-end server to incorrectly interpret the request.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] In this type of HTTP request smuggling, the front end processes the request using Content-Length header while backend processes the request using Transfer-Encoding header.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] The attack would be carried out with the first part of the request declaring a zero length chunk.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] The front end server seeing this would only read the first part of the request and unintentionally pass the second part to the back end server.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] Once passed through to the back end server, it would be treated as the next request and processed, carrying out the attackers hidden request.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] In this type of HTTP request smuggling, the front end processes request using Transfer-Encoding header while backend processes the request using Content-Length header.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] In this attack, a hacker would declare the valid length of the first chunk, which houses the malicious request and then declare a second chunk with a length of 0.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] When the front end server sees the second chunk with a length of 0 it believes the request to be complete and passes it along to the back end server.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] The back end server processes the request using the Content-Length header, however, and as a result the malicious request left in the first chunk go unprocessed until they are treating as being at the start of next request in the sequence and are carried out.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] In this type of HTTP request smuggling, the front end and backend both process the request using Transfer-Encoding header, but the header can be obfuscated in a way (for example by nonstandard whitespace formatting or duplicate headers) that makes one of the servers but not the other one ignore it.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] Obscuring the header may take the form of adding in an incorrect character, such as Transfer-Encoding: xchunked, or an unusual new line character between 'Transfer-Encoding' and ': chunked'.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] If one of the front of back end servers still processes these obfuscated HTTP requests, then the rest of the attack will be similar to how CL.TE or TE.CL attacks work.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] The best prevention to these attacks would clearly be if frontend and backend servers interpreted HTTP requests the same way.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] However, this is usually not an option as load balancers support backend servers run on distinct platforms, using different software.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] Most variants of this attack can be prevented by using HTTP/2, as it uses a different method to determine the length of a request.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] Another method of avoiding the attack is for the frontend server to normalize HTTP requests before passing them to the backend, ensuring that they get interpreted in the same way.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] Configuring a web application firewall is another good way to prevent HRS attacks as many feature technology that identify attack attempts and either blocks or sanitize the suspicious incoming requests.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] (2021) found that most front-end web servers (e.g. proxy servers) provided the parsing features for hindering in practice, all the known HRS attacks on the back-end web servers.
[src:web-application-firewall/http-request-smuggling] (2022) proposed a method using Flask so to implement suitable parsing features that prevent HRS attacks, from a front-end program or web server.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] The platform provides a rule configuration language known as 'SecRules' for real-time monitoring, logging, and filtering of Hypertext Transfer Protocol communications based on user-defined rules.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] Although not its only configuration, ModSecurity is most commonly deployed to provide protections against generic classes of vulnerabilities using the OWASP ModSecurity Core Rule Set (CRS).
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] This is an open-source set of rules written in ModSecurity's SecRules language.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] The project is part of OWASP, the Open Web Application Security Project.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] Several other rule sets are also available.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] To detect threats, the ModSecurity engine is deployed embedded within the webserver or as a proxy server in front of a web application.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] This allows the engine to scan incoming and outgoing HTTP communications to the endpoint.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] Dependent on the rule configuration the engine will decide how communications should be handled which includes the capability to pass, drop, redirect, return a given status code, execute a script, and more.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] ModSecurity was first developed by Ivan Ristić, who wrote the module with the end goal of monitoring application traffic on the Apache HTTP Server.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] The first version was released in November 2002 which supported Apache HTTP Server 1.3.x.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] Starting in 2004 Ivan created Thinking Stone to continue work on the project full-time.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] While working on the version 2.0 rewrite Thinking Stone was bought by Breach Security, an American-Israeli security company, in September 2006.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] Ivan stayed on continuing the development of version 2.0 which was subsequently released in October 2006 at the OWASP AppSec conference in Seattle.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] Ristić and Breach Security released another major rewrite, version 2.5, with major syntactic changes in February 2008.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] In December 2008 Ivan left Breach to found SSL Labs.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] Shortly after Ivan's departure from Breach Security, Trustwave Holdings acquired Breach in June 2010 and relicensed ModSecurity under the Apache license.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] Development continued and the new license allowed easier integration of ModSecurity into other products.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] As a result of this there was steady adoption of ModSecurity by various commercial products.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] The license change also precipitated easier porting of the software.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] Hence, Microsoft contributed an IIS port in August 2012 and the port for Nginx was released at Black Hat Briefings in 2012.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] 2017 saw the second edition of the handbook released, written by Christian Folini and Ivan Ristić.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] It covers ModSecurity up to version 2.9.2.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] Being originally an Apache module, porting ModSecurity to other platforms was time-consuming and had high maintenance costs.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] As a result of this, a complete rewrite was started in December 2015.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] This new iteration, libmodsecurity, changes the underlying architecture, separating ModSecurity into a standalone engine that communicates with the web server via an API.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] This modular architecture-based WAF, which was announced for public use in January 2018, became libmodsecurity (ModSecurity version 3.0) and has supported connectors for Nginx and Apache.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] In 2021, Trustwave Holdings, announce the End-of-Sale (EOS) of Trustwave support for ModSecurity effective August 1, 2021 and the End-of-Life (EOL) of support effective July 1, 2024.
[src:web-application-firewall/modsecurity] The maintenance of the ModSecurity code is given to the open-source community.
[src:web-application-firewall/owasp] Mark Curphey started OWASP on September 9, 2001.
[src:web-application-firewall/owasp] Jeff Williams served as the volunteer Chair of OWASP from late 2003 until September 2011.
[src:web-application-firewall/owasp] As of 2015, Matt Konda chaired the Board.
[src:web-application-firewall/owasp] The OWASP Foundation, a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization in the US established in 2004, supports the OWASP infrastructure and projects.
[src:web-application-firewall/owasp] Since 2011, OWASP is also registered as a non-profit organization in Belgium under the name of OWASP Europe VZW.
[src:web-application-firewall/owasp] In February 2023, it was reported by Bil Corry, a OWASP Foundation Global Board of Directors officer, on Twitter that the board had voted for renaming from the Open Web Application Security Project to its current name, replacing Web with Worldwide.
[src:web-application-firewall/owasp] In May 2023, the OWASP Gen AI Security Project was started to expand the scope of the OWASP Top 10 List to document the most critical risks associated with LLMs.
[src:web-application-firewall/owasp] These certifications help professionals demonstrate expertise in secure development, testing, and application security management across different organizational roles and technical disciplines.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:web-application-firewall/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] A **Web application firewall** (**WAF**) is a specific form of application firewall that filters, monitors, and blocks HTTP traffic to and from a web service.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] By inspecting HTTP traffic, it can prevent attacks exploiting a Web application's known vulnerabilities, such as SQL injection, cross-site scripting (XSS), file inclusion, and improper system configuration.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] Financial institutions often utilize WAFs to help in the mitigation of Web application zero-day vulnerabilities, as well as hard-to-patch bugs or weaknesses through custom attack signature strings.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] Dedicated Web application firewalls entered the market in the late 1990s during a time when web server attacks were becoming more prevalent.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] Early WAF products, from Kavado and Gilian technologies, tried to solve the increasing amount of attacks on Web applications in the late 1990s.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] In 2002, the open-source project ModSecurity was formed in order to make WAF technology more accessible.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] They finalized a core rule set for protecting Web applications, based on OASIS Web Application Security Technical Committee’s (WAS TC) vulnerability work.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] In 2003, they expanded and standardized rules through the Open Web Application Security Project’s (OWASP) Top 10 List, an annual ranking for Web security vulnerabilities.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] This list would become the industry standard for Web application security compliance.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] Since then, the market has continued to grow and evolve, especially focusing on credit card fraud prevention.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] With the development of the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS), a standardization of control over cardholder data, security has become more regulated in this sector.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] A Web application firewall is a special type of application firewall that applies specifically to Web applications.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] It is deployed in front of Web applications and analyzes bi-directional web-based (HTTP) traffic – detecting and blocking anything malicious.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] The OWASP provides a broad technical definition for a WAF as “a security solution on the Web application level which – from a technical point of view – does not depend on the application itself”.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] According to the PCI DSS Information Supplement for requirement 6.6, a WAF is defined as “a security policy enforcement point positioned between a Web application and the client endpoint.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] This functionality can be implemented in software or hardware, running in an appliance device, or in a typical server running a common operating system.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] It may be a stand-alone device or integrated into other network components.” In other words, a WAF can be a virtual or physical appliance that prevents vulnerabilities in Web applications from being exploited by outside threats.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] These vulnerabilities may be because the application itself is a legacy type or was insufficiently coded by design.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] The WAF addresses these code shortcomings by special configurations of rule-sets, also known as policies.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] Previously unknown vulnerabilities can be discovered through penetration testing or via a vulnerability scanner.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] A Web application vulnerability scanner, also known as a web application security scanner, is defined in the SAMATE NIST 500-269 as “an automated program that examines Web applications for potential security vulnerabilities.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] In addition to searching for Web application-specific vulnerabilities, the tools also look for software coding errors.” Resolving vulnerabilities is commonly referred to as remediation.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] Corrections to the code can be made in the application, but typically a more prompt response is necessary.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] In these situations, the application of a custom policy for a unique Web application vulnerability to provide a temporary but immediate fix (known as a virtual patch) may be necessary.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] WAFs are not an ultimate security solution, rather they are meant to be used in conjunction with other network perimeter security solutions such as network firewalls and intrusion prevention systems to provide a holistic defense strategy.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] WAFs typically follow a positive security model, a negative security, or a combination of both as mentioned by the SANS Institute.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] WAFs use a combination of rule-based logic, parsing, and signatures to detect and prevent attacks such as cross-site scripting and SQL injection.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] In general, features like browser emulation, obfuscation and virtualization, and IP obfuscation are used to attempt to bypass WAFs.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] The OWASP produces a list of the top ten Web application security flaws.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] All commercial WAF offerings cover these ten flaws at a minimum.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] There are non-commercial options as well.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] As mentioned earlier, the well-known open-source WAF engine called ModSecurity is one of these options.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] A WAF engine alone is insufficient to provide adequate protection, therefore OWASP along with Trustwave's Spiderlabs help organize and maintain a Core-Rule Set via GitHub to use with the ModSecurity WAF engine.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] Although the names for operating mode may differ, WAFs are basically deployed inline in three different ways.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] According to NSS Labs, deployment options are transparent bridge, transparent reverse proxy, and reverse proxy.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] "Transparent" refers to the fact that the HTTP traffic is sent straight to the Web application, therefore the WAF is transparent between the client and server.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] This is in contrast to reverse proxy, where the WAF acts as a proxy, and the client’s traffic is sent directly to the WAF.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] The WAF then separately sends filtered traffic to Web applications.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] This can provide additional benefits such as IP masking but may introduce disadvantages such as performance latencies.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] JA3, developed by Salesforce in 2017, is a technique for generating a unique fingerprint for SSL/TLS traffic based on specific fields in the handshake, such as the version, cipher suites, and extensions used by the client.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] This fingerprint enables the identification and tracking of clients based on the characteristics of their encrypted traffic.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] In the context of distributed denial of service (DDoS) protection, JA3 fingerprints are used to detect and differentiate malicious traffic, often associated with attack bots, from legitimate traffic, allowing for more precise filtering of potential threats.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] In September 2023, AWS WAF announced built-in support for JA3, enabling customers to inspect the JA3 fingerprints of incoming requests.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-application-firewall] JA3 was deprecated in May 2025 in favor of JA4.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] This article is focused on providing guidance for securing web services and preventing web services related attacks.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] Please notice that due to the difference in implementation between different frameworks, this cheat sheet is kept at a high level.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] Transport confidentiality protects against eavesdropping and man-in-the-middle attacks against web service communications to/from the server.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] User authentication verifies the identity of the user or the system trying to connect to the service.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] Such authentication is usually a function of the container of the web service.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] SOAP encoding styles are meant to move data between software objects into XML format and back again.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] The integrity of data in transit can easily be provided by TLS.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] When using public key cryptography, encryption does guarantee confidentiality but it does not guarantee integrity since the receiver's public key is public.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] For the same reason, encryption does not ensure the identity of the sender.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] Data elements meant to be kept confidential must be encrypted using a strong encryption cipher with an adequate key length to deter brute-forcing.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] Web services need to authorize web service clients the same way web applications authorize users.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] A web service needs to make sure a web service client is authorized to perform a certain action (coarse-grained) on the requested data (fine-grained).
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] Schema validation enforces constraints and syntax defined by the schema.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] Web services need to ensure that the output sent to clients is encoded to be consumed as data and not as scripts.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] This gets pretty important when web service clients use the output to render HTML pages either directly or indirectly using AJAX objects.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] SOAP provides the ability to attach files and documents to SOAP messages.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] This gives the opportunity for hackers to attach viruses and malware to these SOAP messages.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] Web services like web applications could be a target for DOS attacks by automatically sending the web services thousands of large size SOAP messages.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] This either cripples the application making it unable to respond to legitimate messages or it could take it down entirely.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] During regular operation, web services require computational power such as CPU cycles and memory.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] Due to malfunctioning or while under attack, a web service may required too much resources, leaving the host system unstable.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] Throughput represents the number of web service requests served during a specific amount of time.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] XML Denial of Service is probably the most serious attack against web services.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] This protection should be provided by your XML parser/schema validator.
[src:web-application-firewall/web-service-security-cheat-sheet] To verify, build test cases to make sure your parser to resistant to these types of attacks.
